ddress social problems and as an incentive to reduce individual claims on collective resources. Embracing Risk explores this new approach from a variety of perspectives. The first part of the book focuses on the interplay between risk and insurance in various historical and social contexts. The second part examines how risk is used to govern fields outside the realm of insurance, from extreme sports to policing, mental health institutions, and international law. Offering an original approach to risk, insurance, and responsibility, the provocative and wide-ranging essays in Embracing Risk demonstrate that risk has moved well beyond its origins in the insurance trade to become a central organizing principle of social and cultural life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBaker, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Tom, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aClark, Geoffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEricson, Richard V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEwald, François, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaggerty, Kevin D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeimer, Carol A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcCluskey, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aO’Malley, Pat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRose, Nikolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimon, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSimon, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aStone, Deborah, econtributor.4